7 november 1319","1252–1292":"1252–1292","1275–1331":"1275–1331","1256–1319":"1256–1319","1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1292":"1292","7 November 1319":"7 november 1319","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1256":"1256","1331":"1331","about 1256":"circa 1256","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","Great Waltha, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Great Waltham, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, England"},"en":{"about 1256–7 November 1319":"about 1256–7 November 1319","1252–1292":"1252–1292","1275–1331":"1275–1331","1256–1319":"1256–1319","1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1292":"1292","7 November 1319":"7 November 1319","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1256":"1256","1331":"1331","about 1256":"about 1256","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","Great Waltha, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Great Waltham, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the district of Mar in Aberdeenshire, an ancient tribal name probably based on a Brittonic personal name <i>Marsos</i>. There may have been confusion with   Mair   2.","English: habitational name from one or other of various places called from Old Norse <i>marr</i> ‘fen, marsh’, such as Marr, High and Low Marr in Wheldrake, and The Marrs in Swine (all Yorkshire).","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Marro</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Marrs","meanings":["English: variant of   Marr  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Morr","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of German   Marr   3."]},{"name":"Mair","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz, Alois, Benno, Egon, Hans, Hermann, Inge, Kurt, Othmar, Otto, Reinhard, Rudi.","Scottish: variant of   Marr   1.","Scottish: occupational name from Gaelic <i>maor</i> ‘officer’, used specifically for an officer who executed summonses and other legal writs, including not only the king's herald or sergeant but also head foresters and the like. See also   Maver   and compare   Mayer   3."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":3,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":34,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":59,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in